[{"sha":"a063a7050f49cf8c070f8de2f70bce274d7f1518","author":{"name":"j-bernardi","email":"c7fb1083a8e0e494f05049af5d8c1b0768ef2e84@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding multi_dim to class_weight option in fit()

Currently, model.fit(class_weight={}) only works if y_data is of
rank 2 in the output, e.g. (batch_size,) or (batch_size, N_one_hot)
(if N==1, squeeze).

This change adds a flag `class_weight_mode`="multi_dim" to
`model.compile()` that allows dense labels of any shape to be compatible
with `class_weight` in `model.fit()`, asserting that they are either
one_hot encoded or in dense representation with an expanded final
dimension. E.g. necessary for image segmentation or temporal / sequence
data. The relevant tests are included for the DataHandler.

Also adding test that class weight is a dict, and testing existing
class_weight functionality","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/j-bernardi/tensorflow/commits/a063a7050f49cf8c070f8de2f70bce274d7f1518"}]

[{"sha":"da555a2c9bdce45a944ff4c85a2981b79d763724","author":{"name":"Clement Courbet","email":"18a6ad33eeb00c3a39b33c2572bde72aa7e82ab1@google.com"},"message":"Optimize opencv dft by vectorizing radix2 and radix3.

This is useful for non power-of-two sizes when WITH_IPP is not an option.

This shows consistent improvement over openCV benchmarks, and we measure
even larger improvements on our internal workloads.

For example, for 320x480, `32FC*`, we can see a ~5% improvement}, as
`320=2^6*5` and `480=2^5*3*5`, so the improved radix3 version is used.
`64FC*` is flat as expected, as we do not specialize the functors for `double`
in this change.
